{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ce1c741e-ffb7-4712-8525-a4281d747678","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You can find them in:\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for user-space crashes\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-wide\n\nLook for a file matching your process name (e.g., `MyApp-2026-05-10-*.ips`).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n### Core dumps\n\nmacOS disables core dumps by default. To enable them for future crashes:\n\n```bash\nsudo launchctl limit core unlimited\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nCores are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` crash log is usually sufficient — it contains the faulting thread's backtrace, register state, and loaded images. You can symbolicate the .NET runtime frames using `atos` and debug symbols from the Microsoft symbol server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c9e4e05c-9492-485b-9203-25bcfe158c2a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":316,"requestId":"6086:2DB10D:2B84DB:3957F3:69FFE41D"},"id":"2cea37f7-d71a-49aa-ba09-f25184050626","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:49:26.396Z","parentId":"d9a76a4c-acb6-403c-b427-b88a460a593c"}
